=========================================
      WRAPPER CLASSES IN JAVA
=========================================

1. INTRODUCTION
---------------
Wrapper classes in Java are used to convert primitive data types into objects. 
Java is an object-oriented programming language, but primitive types (int, 
char, double, etc.) are not objects.

To use primitives in collections or object-based operations, Java provides 
corresponding wrapper classes located in the java.lang package.

Primitive Type     Wrapper Class
--------------     -------------
byte               Byte
short              Short
int                Integer
long               Long
float              Float
double             Double
char               Character
boolean            Boolean


2. WHY WRAPPER CLASSES ARE REQUIRED
-----------------------------------
- Primitive types cannot be used in Java Collections (ArrayList, HashMap, etc.).
- Collections only work with objects.

Example:
ArrayList<int>      -> NOT ALLOWED
ArrayList<Integer>  -> ALLOWED

- Wrapper classes allow primitive values to be treated as objects.


3. AUTOBOXING AND UNBOXING
--------------------------
Autoboxing: 
Automatic conversion of primitive type into its corresponding wrapper object.
Example: 
int a = 10;
Integer obj = a;

Unboxing: 
Automatic conversion of wrapper object into primitive type.
Example: 
Integer obj = 20;
int b = obj;


4. IMPORTANT METHODS
--------------------
- parseInt():  Converts String to primitive type.
               Example: int num = Integer.parseInt("100");

- valueOf():   Converts String or primitive to wrapper object.
               Example: Integer obj = Integer.valueOf(50);

- toString():  Converts primitive or wrapper to String.
               Example: String s = Integer.toString(200);

- compareTo(): Used to compare two wrapper objects.


5. IMMUTABILITY
---------------
Wrapper classes are immutable. Once an object is created, its value cannot 
be changed.

Example:
Integer x = 10;
x = 20; 
// A new object is created instead of modifying the existing one.


6. INTEGER CACHING
------------------
Integer values between -128 to 127 are cached by the JVM. If you create 
Integer objects within this range, the JVM reuses the same object.

Example:
Integer a = 100, b = 100;
a == b;  // true (Same reference)

Integer x = 200, y = 200;
x == y;  // false (Different objects in memory)


7. REAL-TIME USAGE
------------------
- Used in Collections (ArrayList, etc.)
- Used in JDBC and database operations
- Used in parsing user input
- Used in Spring Boot request parameters
- Used when null values are required (Primitives cannot be null)


8. DIFFERENCE: PRIMITIVE VS WRAPPER
-----------------------------------
PRIMITIVE:
- Stores actual value
- Faster
- Cannot store null
- Not an object

WRAPPER:
- Stores object reference
- Slightly slower
- Can store null
- Works with Collections
=========================================
